<bioghist encodinganalog="545">
<p>Isaac Newton Elwood was born in Starkville, Herkimer County, New York, May 11, 1843. He graduated from the University of Michigan in 1867. Soon thereafter, he was admitted on trial to the Detroit Annual Conference of the Methodist Episcopal Church. His ministerial appointments were: Marquette, 1867-1868; Fenton, 1869; Saginaw, 1870-1871; Morenci, 1872-1874; Ann Arbor, 1875; Port Huron, 1876; Port Huron District, 1877-1880; Ypsilanti, 1881-1883, and Court Street in Flint, 1884-1885. He died in Flint, January 19, 1887.</p>
</bioghist>



<scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
<p>The Elwood collection consists of sermons and outlines and notes for sermons delivered in Marquette, Fenton, Saginaw, Morenci, Ann Arbor, Port Huron, Ypsilanti, and Flint, Michigan. Also included are sermons on temperance, an essay on Charles Sumner (1866), and a brief history of Sunday School in Morenci, Michigan. </p>
</scopecontent>

